Methods for classification

Show the results from the six classification methods.

Logistic regression

  • From Chi-squared test, \(p-value < \alpha\) for common \(\alpha\) values \((0.1, 0.01, 0.001, 0.0001)\), so there is evidence from the fitting model that the coefficients we found are not fitting the data well.
  • And the accuracy we found is \(0.59\), with a precision of \(0.5855\) and a recall of \(0.9792\).
  • For the testing data, we got a \(p-value\) of \(0.0008434\), which is greater than \(\alpha\) when \(\alpha = 0.0001\). As a conclusion, using logsitic regression is an acceptable choice but not the best one.

dat <- read.csv("paroledat.csv", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
dat <- dat %>% dplyr::select(sex, "race"=race...ethnicity, "crime1" = crime.1...class, "decision" = interview.decision, "min" = aggregated.minimum.sentence, "max" = aggregated.maximum.sentence) %>% filter(decision != "*", decision != "**********", crime1 != "")
dat$min <- str_sub(dat$min,1,2)
dat$max <- str_sub(dat$max,1,2)
dat$min <- as.numeric(dat$min)
dat$max <- as.numeric(dat$max)
# Note: 0 for not denied and 1 for denied
dat$decision[which(dat$decision != "DENIED")] <- 1
dat$decision[which(dat$decision == "DENIED")] <- 0
train <- dat[1:30000,]
test <- dat[30001:39890,]
model <- glm(as.numeric(decision)~sex+race+crime1+min+max, family='binomial', data=train)

# Evaluation
anova(model, test="Chisq")

dat <- read.csv("paroledat.csv", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
dat <- dat %>% dplyr::select(sex, "race"=race...ethnicity, "crime1" = crime.1...class, "decision" = interview.decision, "min" = aggregated.minimum.sentence, "max" = aggregated.maximum.sentence) %>% filter(decision != "*", decision != "**********", crime1 != "")
dat$min <- str_sub(dat$min,1,2)

dat$max <- as.numeric(dat$max)
dat$decision[which(dat$decision != "DENIED")] <- "NOTD"

roc<-performance(pred,"tpr","fpr")
plot(roc)

K nearest neighbors

  • The model reports as “too many ties in KNN”, which is because of the data has too many similar results or repetitions around one k value. We can’t get the classification result from the table above. But we do have typed the code that we can calculate the value of accuracy, precision, recall, and ROC curve. Thus, the method of k nearest neighbors is not suitable for this data.

Support vector machines

  • We do not distinguish the test and training data using SVM method.

  • We can get the classification result from the table above and then we can calculate the value of accuracy, precision and recall. The values are 0.5975394, 0.9413137 and 0.595802. The result of precision is much better than logistic regression but the result of recall is worse.

  • From the ROC curve, we think the result of SVM method is not very good and this may be a result of the data we choose does not have enough information for us to use this method.

# We often use SVM to do classificationif the boundary between classes non-linear class
# boundaries. The method of SVM is to map the data into a new space and transform them
# into linearly separable data in the new space.

dat <- read.csv("paroledat.csv", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
dat <- dat %>% dplyr::select(sex, "race"=race...ethnicity, "crime1" = crime.1...class, "decision" = interview.decision, "min" = aggregated.minimum.sentence, "max" = aggregated.maximum.sentence) %>% filter(decision != "*", decision != "**********", crime1 != "")
dat$min <- str_sub(dat$min,1,2)
dat$max <- str_sub(dat$max,1,2)
dat$min <- as.numeric(dat$min)
dat$max <- as.numeric(dat$max)
dat$decision[which(dat$decision != "DENIED")] <- "NOTD"
dat$decision[which(dat$decision == "DENIED")] <- "D"

dat$crime1[which(dat$crime1 =='A')]<-0
dat$crime1[which(dat$crime1 =='B')]<-1
dat$crime1[which(dat$crime1 =='C')]<-2
dat$crime1[which(dat$crime1 =='D')]<-3
dat$crime1[which(dat$crime1 =='E')]<-4

dat$race[which(dat$race =='WHITE')]<-0
dat$race[which(dat$race =='BLACK')]<-1
dat$race[which(dat$race =='HISPANIC')]<-2
dat$race[which(dat$race =='AMER IND/ALSK')]<-3
dat$race[which(dat$race =='ASIAN/PACIFIC')]<-4
dat$race[which(dat$race =='UNKNOWN')]<-5
dat$race[which(dat$race =='OTHER')]<-6

dat$sex[which(dat$sex =='MALE')]<-0
dat$sex[which(dat$sex =='FEMALE')]<-1

dat$race <- as.numeric(dat$race)
dat$sex <- as.numeric(dat$sex)
dat$crime1 <- as.numeric(dat$crime1)
dat$min <- as.numeric(dat$min)
dat$max <- as.numeric(dat$max)
dat$decision <- as.factor(dat$decision)

new <-na.omit(dat)



dat_svm_model <- svm(decision ~., probability = TRUE , data = dat)
dat_svm_model
## 
## Call:
## svm(formula = decision ~ ., data = dat, probability = TRUE)
## 
## 
## Parameters:
##    SVM-Type:  C-classification 
##  SVM-Kernel:  radial 
##        cost:  1 
##       gamma:  0.2 
## 
## Number of Support Vectors:  30932
dat_svm_model_pred <- predict(dat_svm_model, dat[,-4])
prediction <- predict(dat_svm_model, probability = TRUE, new[,-4])
c <- attr(prediction, "probabilities")

dat_table <- table(pred = dat_svm_model_pred,true = new[,4])
dat_table
##       true
## pred       D  NOTD
##   D    20579 13961
##   NOTD  1283  2054
# We can get the classification result from the table above and then we can calculate the 
# value of accuracy, precision and recall. The values are  0.5975394, 0.9413137 and 0.595802.

accuracy <- sum(diag(dat_table))/sum(dat_table)
accuracy
## [1] 0.5975394
precision <- dat_table[1, 1]/sum(dat_table[, 1])
precision
## [1] 0.9413137
recall <- dat_table[1, 1]/sum(dat_table[1,])
recall
## [1] 0.595802
roc <- roc(new[,4], c[, 1])
plot(roc, col = "skyblue")
